linux is a kernal based on character user interface.it helps us to 
understand the working of computer system more effiently.
One of the basic linux is ubuntu .
some of the basic commands used in ubuntu are:
* mkdir   - used in making of new directory .
* cd - to change directories
* cd .. - to go the previous directory .
* ls - list all the directories present in folder.
* ls-a  - list hidden files also.
* pwd - gives the name of the present directory etc etc,

            permission in ubuntu is given in 9 digits.

* r - for reading only .
* w - for writing also .
* x - for execution of file
permission is given by command :
*sudo chmod rwx _w_ ___ {file name }
or 
*sudo chmod -R 777 {address of file name }
      for giving ownership of any folder/file:
*sudo chown -R yourusername {address of file}

 first 3 is given for user next 3 for   group and next 3 for others.
                    Ubuntu is  a case sensitive language.
   there are many more commands in ubuntu to learn.


shortcuts used in ubuntu linux terminal


clt+alt+T -> used for opening a new terminal.
clt+shift+T -> used for opening a new tav in terminal 
clt+L -> used for clearing a terminal screen .
clt+A-> used for jumping to the first letter for aommand 
clt+R ->used for opening the reverse menu (it search all the command that we have previously entered using the tags given by you)
clt+Z -> stop any process .

              sudo is a special tag if used before any command ,gives the superuser permission that is it allocts all the permissions required for accesing that commands
          
         It can be used as:

-> sudo {command}
or -> {command}
       sudo!!

   sudo commands requires password authentication of the administrator.
  one more interesting command used in terminal is 
....* ssh
 we can access different computers on same network using ssh(secure shell) command :
 -> ssh your_pc_name@ip_address
